# Supply Chain Disruption War Game
#
# A live, reactive multi-agent network simulating a small supply chain:
#   2 Suppliers -> 1 Logistics/routing layer -> 1 Warehouse -> 3 Retail demand points
#
# Unlike a linear pipeline, this network shares one live "world state" (see
# coded_tools/supply_chain_war_game/world_state.py) that every agent's coded
# tools read from and write to. A disruption injected mid-conversation
# (port strike, supplier going offline, demand spike) is immediately visible
# to every other agent on their next tool call, so the mesh has to detect
# it, argue about trade-offs, and re-plan live -- with the Coordinator
# making the final cost vs. speed vs. risk call.
#
# HOW TO RUN THE DEMO:
#   1. python -m neuro_san_studio run
#   2. Open http://localhost:4173/ and pick "supply_chain_war_game"
#   3. Ask for a status briefing, e.g.:
#        "Give me a full status briefing on the supply chain."
#   4. Let it run a couple of turns normally, then inject a live disruption
#      via plain language, e.g.:
#        "Port strike at Supplier A's port, severity severe."
#        "Supplier B just went offline."
#        "Demand at Retail_West just spiked 2.5x."
#   5. Ask the Coordinator to re-plan:
#        "Given that, what should we do? Optimize for speed this time."
#   6. To reset between demo runs:
#        "Reset the simulation to baseline."

{
    # Optional metadata describing this agent network
    "metadata": {
        "description": "A live, reactive multi-agent supply chain war game: 2 Suppliers -> Logistics -> Warehouse -> 3 Retail demand points, sharing one live world state. Inject disruptions (port strikes, supplier outages, demand spikes) mid-conversation and watch the network detect, argue, and re-plan in real time.",
        "tags": ["multi-agent", "simulation", "supply-chain", "live-state", "war-game"],
        "sample_queries": [
            "Give me a full status briefing on the supply chain.",
            "Port strike at Supplier A's port, severity severe.",
            "Supplier B just went offline.",
            "Demand at Retail_West just spiked 2.5x.",
            "Given that, what should we do? Optimize for speed this time.",
            "Reset the simulation to baseline."
        ]
    },

    include "registries/aaosa.hocon"

    include "config/llm_config.hocon"

    "instructions_prefix": """
You are one agent inside a live "Supply Chain Disruption War Game" simulation.
This is a real-time multi-agent network, not a linear pipeline: conditions can
change mid-conversation because a disruption event (port strike, supplier
outage, demand spike) may be injected at any time by the user or by another
agent. Always re-check live data via your tools before answering -- never
assume the network is still in the state it was a few turns ago.
Only answer inquiries that are directly within your area of expertise.
Do not try to help with matters outside your role.
Do not mention what you can NOT do. Only mention what you can do.
""",

    "tools": [
        # ================= FRONT MAN =================
        {
            "name": "SupplyChainCoordinator",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": """
The Coordinator of a live 2-supplier / 1-logistics / 1-warehouse / 3-retail
supply chain war game. Give status briefings, detect and explain live
disruptions, and make the final trade-off call between cost, speed, and
risk when the network needs to re-plan.
                """
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is SupplyChainCoordinator. You are the final decision-maker for
this supply chain network.

Your job:
1. When asked for a status briefing, call ALL of your down-chain agents
   (DisruptionControlRoom, SupplierRelationsManager, LogisticsPlanner,
   WarehouseOperations, DemandForecastingUnit) to assemble a full live
   picture, then summarize it clearly: suppliers' status, best shipping
   routes, warehouse days-of-supply, and retail demand -- and flag any
   active disruptions.
2. When the user injects a disruption in plain language (e.g. "there's a
   port strike at Supplier A", "Supplier B is offline", "demand spiked at
   Retail_West"), translate it into a call to DisruptionControlRoom to
   actually apply it to the live world state. Then immediately re-query the
   other agents to see the downstream impact, and report what changed.
3. When asked to re-plan or decide what to do, gather fresh input from
   SupplierRelationsManager, LogisticsPlanner, WarehouseOperations, and
   DemandForecastingUnit, weigh the trade-offs between cost, speed
   (lead time / transit time), and risk, and make a single clear final
   recommendation -- e.g. "Shift 60% of volume to Supplier B via land
   freight for the next 3 weeks; accept the +$0.40/unit cost to avoid the
   port-strike delay, since warehouse days-of-supply would otherwise drop
   below safety stock." Always state what you are optimizing for and what
   you are trading away.
4. If the user asks to reset the simulation, delegate that to
   DisruptionControlRoom.

Never fabricate numbers -- always get them live from your down-chain agents.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": [
                "DisruptionControlRoom",
                "SupplierRelationsManager",
                "LogisticsPlanner",
                "WarehouseOperations",
                "DemandForecastingUnit"
            ]
        },

        # ================= DISRUPTION CONTROL ROOM =================
        {
            "name": "DisruptionControlRoom",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": """
Controls live disruption events on the network: injecting port strikes,
supplier outages, or demand spikes; resolving them; resetting the whole
simulation to baseline; and reporting full simulation status.
                """
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is DisruptionControlRoom. You are the "game master" interface for
this war game.

- To inject a disruption, call InjectDisruptionTool with:
    "event_type": "port_strike" | "supplier_offline" | "demand_spike"
    "target": a supplier_id ("Supplier_A" or "Supplier_B") for port_strike
        and supplier_offline, or a retail_id ("Retail_North", "Retail_South",
        or "Retail_West") for demand_spike
    "severity": "minor" | "moderate" | "severe" (default "moderate")
    "multiplier": optional explicit override, mainly for demand_spike
    "notes": optional free-text color
  Map natural language to these values yourself. For example "the port at
  Long Beach is on strike" -> target "Supplier_A" (that's the supplier whose
  route runs through that port). "Retail West demand tripled" -> target
  "Retail_West", multiplier 3.0.
- To resolve/undo a specific disruption, call InjectDisruptionTool with
  event_type "resolve_event" and target set to the disruption's id (e.g.
  "DISR-001"), or "all" to clear every active disruption.
- To reset the ENTIRE simulation back to nominal baseline, call
  ResetSimulationTool.
- To report the full current simulation state and active disruptions, call
  SimulationStatusTool.

Always report back exactly what changed (the message returned by your
tools), so the rest of the network and the user can see the concrete effect.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": ["InjectDisruptionTool", "ResetSimulationTool", "SimulationStatusTool"]
        },
        {
            "name": "InjectDisruptionTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Injects (or resolves) a live disruption event into the shared world state.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "event_type": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "enum": ["port_strike", "supplier_offline", "demand_spike", "resolve_event"],
                            "description": "The type of disruption event to apply."
                        },
                        "target": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Supplier_A/Supplier_B for port_strike/supplier_offline, Retail_North/Retail_South/Retail_West for demand_spike, or a disruption id / 'all' for resolve_event."
                        },
                        "severity": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "enum": ["minor", "moderate", "severe"],
                            "description": "How severe the disruption is. Defaults to moderate."
                        },
                        "multiplier": {
                            "type": "float",
                            "default": 1.0,
                            "description": "Optional explicit multiplier override, mainly used for demand_spike."
                        },
                        "notes": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional free-text color/context for the scenario."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["event_type", "target"]
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.disruption_control.InjectDisruption"
        },
        {
            "name": "ResetSimulationTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Resets the entire supply chain simulation back to its nominal baseline.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "confirm": {
                            "type": "boolean",
                            "description": "Optional confirmation flag to reset the simulation."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.disruption_control.ResetSimulation"
        },
        {
            "name": "SimulationStatusTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Returns the full current simulation state, active disruptions, and recent event log.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "reason": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional reason for requesting the current simulation status."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.disruption_control.GetSimulationStatus"
        },

        # ================= SUPPLIER SIDE =================
        {
            "name": "SupplierRelationsManager",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": """
Manages relationships with both suppliers, protecting their margins and
lead times, and reports each supplier's live status.
                """
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is SupplierRelationsManager. Your objective is to protect
supplier margins and lead times while giving an honest live read on
capacity and risk.
Call SupplierAAgent and SupplierBAgent to get each supplier's current
status (online/offline, capacity, lead time, unit cost, shipping route
health), then summarize both together so the requester can compare them.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": ["SupplierAAgent", "SupplierBAgent"]
        },
        {
            "name": "SupplierAAgent",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": "Reports live status for Supplier A (Vietnam, electronics sub-assemblies, ocean freight)."
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is SupplierAAgent. You represent Supplier A only. Your objective
is to protect Supplier A's margin and lead-time commitments. Call
SupplierAStatusAPI to get your live status and route health, and report it
honestly, including if you have gone offline or your route is disrupted.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": ["SupplierAStatusAPI"]
        },
        {
            "name": "SupplierBAgent",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": "Reports live status for Supplier B (Mexico, final assembly parts, land freight)."
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is SupplierBAgent. You represent Supplier B only. Your objective
is to protect Supplier B's margin and lead-time commitments. Call
SupplierBStatusAPI to get your live status and route health, and report it
honestly, including if you have gone offline or your route is disrupted.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": ["SupplierBStatusAPI"]
        },
        {
            "name": "SupplierAStatusAPI",
            "function": {
                "description": "Returns Supplier A's live status and shipping route health.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "reason": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional reason for checking Supplier A's status."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.supplier_status.SupplierAStatusAPI"
        },
        {
            "name": "SupplierBStatusAPI",
            "function": {
                "description": "Returns Supplier B's live status and shipping route health.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "reason": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional reason for checking Supplier B's status."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.supplier_status.SupplierBStatusAPI"
        },

        # ================= LOGISTICS =================
        {
            "name": "LogisticsPlanner",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": """
Plans and optimizes shipping routes from both suppliers to the warehouse,
minimizing cost and distance/time while tracking route risk.
                """
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is LogisticsPlanner. Your objective is to minimize shipping cost
and transit time across both supplier routes, while staying aware of risk.
Call RouteOptimizerTool (pass "prioritize": "cost", "speed", or "risk" based
on what's being asked -- default to "cost" if not specified) to get live
route comparisons, then explain the ranked recommendation in plain terms,
including whether either supplier is currently unavailable.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": ["RouteOptimizerTool"]
        },
        {
            "name": "RouteOptimizerTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Compares both supplier shipping routes live and ranks them by cost, speed, or risk.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "prioritize": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "enum": ["cost", "speed", "risk"],
                            "description": "Which factor to optimize the ranking for. Defaults to cost."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.logistics.RouteOptimizer"
        },

        # ================= WAREHOUSE =================
        {
            "name": "WarehouseOperations",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": """
Manages the central warehouse's inventory position, avoiding stockouts and
overstock given live retail demand and incoming supply.
                """
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is WarehouseOperations. Your objective is to avoid both stockouts
and overstock. Call WarehouseInventoryTool to get your live inventory
position, days-of-supply given current total retail demand, and stockout/
overstock risk flags, then report them clearly, calling out any risk.

If the user tells you stock has physically changed -- a shipment was
received, units were damaged/written off, a manual count correction, etc.
-- call AdjustInventoryTool with "units" (positive to add, negative to
remove) and a short "reason", then report the new total and whether that
changes your stockout/overstock read.

If the user asks you to advance time / simulate a week passing / run
replenishment (e.g. "run the weekly replenishment", "simulate next week",
"let a week go by"), call RunWeeklyReplenishmentTool. This ships each
ONLINE supplier's full weekly capacity into the warehouse (an OFFLINE
supplier contributes zero), capped at warehouse capacity. Report the
per-supplier breakdown, how much was actually received, and flag if any
units overflowed because the warehouse was full.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": ["WarehouseInventoryTool", "AdjustInventoryTool", "RunWeeklyReplenishmentTool"]
        },
        {
            "name": "WarehouseInventoryTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Returns live warehouse inventory position and stockout/overstock risk.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "reason": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional reason for checking warehouse inventory."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.warehouse.WarehouseInventoryChecker"
        },
        {
            "name": "AdjustInventoryTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Adds or removes units from the warehouse's current stock on hand (e.g. a shipment arrived, or units were damaged/written off).",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "units": {
                            "type": "float",
                            "description": "Signed number of units to apply. Positive adds stock, negative removes it."
                        },
                        "reason": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Short free-text reason for the change, e.g. 'inbound shipment received'."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["units"]
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.warehouse.AdjustInventory"
        },
        {
            "name": "RunWeeklyReplenishmentTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Advances the simulation by one week: each online supplier ships its full weekly capacity into the warehouse (capped at warehouse capacity); offline suppliers ship nothing.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "notes": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional free-text context, e.g. 'week 3 of the demo'."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.warehouse.RunWeeklyReplenishment"
        },


        # ================= DEMAND FORECAST =================
        {
            "name": "DemandForecastingUnit",
            "function": ${aaosa_call}{
                "description": """
Forecasts and reports what retail demand actually looks like right now
across all three retail points, flagging any spikes above baseline.
                """
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
Your name is DemandForecastingUnit. Your objective is to accurately predict
and report what retail actually needs. Call DemandForecastTool to get live
demand at each retail point vs. its baseline, and flag any that are
spiking, with the percentage above baseline.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "tools": ["DemandForecastTool"]
        },
        {
            "name": "DemandForecastTool",
            "function": {
                "description": "Returns live demand at each retail point vs. baseline, flagging spikes.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "reason": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Optional reason for checking demand forecast."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": []
                }
            },
            "class": "coded_tools.supply_chain_war_game.demand_forecast.DemandForecastAPI"
        }
    ]
}
